postcontent: I have a very rare Beretta BM59 semi-auto rifle.  Comes with two genuine Beretta BM59 magazines (extremely rare also).  Also has the built-in folding bipod.  Excellent condition. Beretta designed the BM59, which was essentially a full auto or semi-auto M14 fitted with a removable 20-round magazine, folding bipod, and flash suppressor/grenade launcher.  The BM 59 was adopted in 1959 and served the Italian military.  Other makers were licenced to produce for the Argentinian, Indonesian, Danish, and Moroccan armies (others also, I believe).  This one was actually made by Beretta as proven by the stampings.  This is a real BM59, not a converted BM62 (civilian version).

From the Standard Catalog of Smith and Wesson, This is very simila to the Chiefs Special Airweight with the obvious distinguishing characteristic of having the frame built up a the top of the rear to form and integral shroud for the hammer.
